The '''Washington & Jefferson College Energy Index''' is an index measuring [[United States energy independence|American energy independence]].<ref name=home>{{cite web | title =Energy Index | work = | publisher =[[Washington & Jefferson College]] Center for Energy Policy & Management | url =http://www.washjeff.edu/center-energy-policy-management/energy-index | accessdate = December 16, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CyCx3Dls |archivedate=December 16, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Karlovitz | first =Bob | title =Washington & Jefferson College to offer stage for energy discussions | newspaper =[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]] | date =February 23, 2013 | url =http://triblive.com/business/headlines/3032200-74/energy-college-stares | accessdate = September 22, 2013}}</ref>  The Index describes the amount of energy produced in America versus the total [[energy consumption]] in America.<ref name=home />  On a scale of 1 to 100, 1 represents total dependence and 100 represents total independence.<ref name=home />  In 2012, the Index was 74.<ref name=graphic>{{cite web | title =Energy Index Infographic  | work = | publisher =[[Washington & Jefferson College]] Center for Energy Policy & Management | url =http://www.washjeff.edu/cepm/energy-index | accessdate = December 16, 2012|archivedate=December 16, 2012| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CyC0z6pK }}</ref>  Regional figures are produced, and historical figures have been developed back to 1949.<ref name=home />  The Index showed that by 2012, American energy independence had decreased by 22% since the tenure of President [[Harry Truman]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Luna  | first =Taryn | title =W&J College index details U.S. energy consumption | newspaper =[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] | date =April 30, 2012  | url =http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/news/environment/wj-college-index-details-us-energy-consumption-633729/ | accessdate = December 16, 2012}}</ref>

The Index is authored by Professors Leslie Dunn and Robert Dunn, of the [[Washington & Jefferson College]] Department of Economics and Business.<ref name=index>{{cite web | last =Dunn | first =Leslie  |author2=Robert Dunn  | title =W&J Energy Index - U.S. Energy Overview and Index Technical Notes | work = | publisher =Washington & Jefferson College, Department of Economics and Business | date =February 27, 2012 | url =http://www.washjeff.edu/sites/default/files/uploadedfiles/cepm/W%26J_Energy_Index.pdf | format =PDF | accessdate =December 16, 2012| archivedate=December 16, 2012| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CyCIs42N }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Reid | first =Robert | title =Professors Design Index to Measure Nation's Progress Toward Energy Index | work =W&J Magazine | publisher =[[Washington & Jefferson College]] | date =Summer 2012| page=10 | url =http://issuu.com/vanikdesign/docs/wj_mag_summer12 | format =PDF | accessdate =  December 16, 2012}}
</ref>  The Index utilizes publicly available energy data, analyzed with a proprietary [[algorithm]].<ref>{{cite web | last =Stares | first =Diana | title =The Washington & Jefferson College Energy Index | work = Executive Summary| publisher =W&J Center for Energy Policy and Management | url =http://www.washjeff.edu/sites/default/files/uploadedfiles/cepm/CEPM_ExecSum.pdf | format =PDF | accessdate =  December 16, 2012 | archivedate=December 16, 2012| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cxn5zytz}}</ref>  Additionally, the energy index has also been used to analyze more local energy use, including [[Washington & Jefferson College]] energy use in dormitories from 2001-2012.<ref>{{cite press release | title =How Many College Students Does it Take to Change a Light Bulb? Electricity Usage in a Dorm Room 2001-2012 | publisher =[[Washington & Jefferson College]] | date =September 6, 2012  | url =http://www.prweb.com/releases/2012/9/prweb9870685.htm | accessdate =  December 16, 2012 | archivedate=December 16, 2012 | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cxn3UIZf}}</ref>

The index is reproduced as an [[infographic]]  by the [[Associated Press]] for national distribution.<ref>{{cite news | title =Washington and Jefferson College Center for Energy Policy and Management launches first-ever W&J Energy Index| newspaper =[[Associated Press]]| date =April 23, 2012 | url =http://www.apimages.com/oneup.aspx?st=id&id=69accf2fa2424f949877baadb0a28592 | accessdate = December 16, 2012| archivedate=December 16, 2012| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cxmzn7Q5 }}</ref>

The Index was unveiled in 2012's W&J Energy Summit, with [[Susan Eisenhower]], of [[The Eisenhower Institute]], and journalist [[Eleanor Clift]] leading the discussions.<ref>{{cite web | last =| first =| title =Eisenhower and Clift Headline first W&J Energy Summit| work =W&J Magazine | publisher =[[Washington & Jefferson College]] | date =Summer 2012| page=11 | url =http://issuu.com/vanikdesign/docs/wj_mag_summer12 | format =PDF | accessdate =  December 16, 2012}}</ref>

